#title: TypeScript Strict Mode Adoption Skill
#author: AIF Migration Team

@skill[name="typescript-strict-mode", version="1.0", profile=migration]
  @precondition
    Repository uses TypeScript with tsconfig.json present.
    strict is not already set to true in tsconfig.json.
    Project builds successfully before migration.
    Some or all of the strict sub-flags are currently disabled:
    strictNullChecks, strictFunctionTypes, strictBindCallApply,
    strictPropertyInitialization, noImplicitAny, noImplicitThis,
    alwaysStrict, useUnknownInCatchVariables.
  @end

  @step[order=1]
    Phase 1 — Enable alwaysStrict and strictBindCallApply.
    These are the least disruptive strict flags:
    - alwaysStrict: Emits 'use strict' in all output files
    - strictBindCallApply: Type-checks bind, call, apply arguments

    Set in tsconfig.json:
      "compilerOptions": {
        "alwaysStrict": true,
        "strictBindCallApply": true
      }

    Fix any resulting errors (usually few):
    - Incorrect bind/call/apply argument types
    - Functions called with wrong argument counts via .call()
  @end

  @step[order=2]
    Phase 2 — Enable noImplicitThis.
    Functions that use `this` without explicit type annotation will error.

    Common fixes:
    - Add explicit `this` parameter: function handler(this: HTMLElement, e: Event)
    - Convert to arrow functions where `this` refers to lexical scope
    - Add `this: void` to callbacks that don't use `this`

    Before:
      element.addEventListener('click', function(e) {
        this.classList.add('active'); // Error: 'this' implicitly has type 'any'
      });

    After:
      element.addEventListener('click', function(this: HTMLElement, e: Event) {
        this.classList.add('active');
      });
    Or:
      element.addEventListener('click', (e) => {
        element.classList.add('active');
      });
  @end

  @step[order=3]
    Phase 3 — Enable noImplicitAny.
    This is typically the most impactful flag. Variables, parameters, and
    return types that cannot be inferred will require explicit annotations.

    Priority order for fixing:
    1. Function parameters — most common source of implicit any
    2. Variable declarations without initializers
    3. Object destructuring without type context
    4. Callback parameters in higher-order functions

    Common patterns:
    - function process(data) → function process(data: ProcessInput)
    - const items = [] → const items: Item[] = []
    - .map((item) => ...) — usually inferred, but check
    - catch (error) → catch (error: unknown) or catch (error: Error)

    For large files with many implicit-any errors, consider adding
    per-file @ts-expect-error or @ts-ignore comments as temporary
    markers, then fixing in subsequent commits.
  @end

  @step[order=4]
    Phase 4 — Enable strictNullChecks.
    This is the most valuable strict flag for catching real bugs.
    Variables typed as T can no longer implicitly be null or undefined.

    Common patterns to fix:
    - Optional chaining: obj.prop → obj?.prop
    - Nullish coalescing: value || default → value ?? default
    - Explicit null checks: if (value !== null && value !== undefined)
    - Non-null assertion (use sparingly): value!
    - Type narrowing: if (typeof x === 'string') { ... }
    - Map.get() returns T | undefined (add existence checks)
    - Array.find() returns T | undefined (add existence checks)
    - DOM queries return Element | null (add null checks)

    Before:
      const user = getUser(id);
      console.log(user.name); // May be null!

    After:
      const user = getUser(id);
      if (!user) throw new Error(`User ${id} not found`);
      console.log(user.name);
  @end

  @step[order=5]
    Phase 5 — Enable strictFunctionTypes.
    Function parameter types are checked contravariantly.
    This catches unsafe function assignments.

    Before:
      type Handler = (event: Event) => void;
      const handler: Handler = (event: MouseEvent) => { ... };
      // Unsafe: Handler could be called with KeyboardEvent

    After:
      type Handler = (event: MouseEvent) => void;
      const handler: Handler = (event: MouseEvent) => { ... };

    Common fixes:
    - Narrow callback parameter types to match expected usage
    - Use function overloads for handlers accepting multiple event types
    - Update generic constraints on utility types
  @end

  @step[order=6]
    Phase 6 — Enable strictPropertyInitialization.
    Class properties must be initialized in the constructor or declaration.

    Common fixes:
    - Add initializer: private name: string = '';
    - Initialize in constructor: this.name = name;
    - Use definite assignment assertion (sparingly): private name!: string;
    - Make optional: private name?: string;

    For dependency-injected properties (Angular, NestJS, etc.),
    the definite assignment assertion (!) is appropriate since the
    DI framework guarantees initialization.
  @end

  @step[order=7]
    Phase 7 — Enable useUnknownInCatchVariables.
    Catch clause variables are typed as `unknown` instead of `any`.

    Before:
      try { ... } catch (error) {
        console.log(error.message); // error is 'any'
      }

    After:
      try { ... } catch (error) {
        if (error instanceof Error) {
          console.log(error.message);
        } else {
          console.log(String(error));
        }
      }
  @end

  @step[order=8]
    Final step — Replace individual flags with strict: true.
    Once all individual strict flags are enabled and all errors fixed,
    replace the individual flags with the single strict flag.

    Before:
      "compilerOptions": {
        "alwaysStrict": true,
        "strictBindCallApply": true,
        "noImplicitThis": true,
        "noImplicitAny": true,
        "strictNullChecks": true,
        "strictFunctionTypes": true,
        "strictPropertyInitialization": true,
        "useUnknownInCatchVariables": true
      }

    After:
      "compilerOptions": {
        "strict": true
      }

    Verify the build still passes after this consolidation.
  @end

  @verify
    tsconfig.json contains `"strict": true`.
    No remaining individual strict sub-flags in tsconfig.json.
    No `@ts-ignore` comments added by the migration (only pre-existing ones).
    No remaining `as any` type assertions added by the migration.
    Build succeeds with `tsc --noEmit`.
    All existing tests pass.
  @end

  @fallback
    If a module has more than 50 noImplicitAny errors, add it to
    a tsconfig.strict-exclude.json and flag for incremental migration.

    If third-party type definitions are incompatible with strictFunctionTypes,
    add targeted type assertion wrappers and document the incompatibility.

    If legacy class hierarchies make strictPropertyInitialization impractical,
    use the definite assignment assertion (!) with a comment explaining why.

    For strictNullChecks on database query results, prefer runtime validation
    (e.g., zod schemas) over non-null assertions to catch actual null values.
  @end

  @output_contract
    TypeScript compiles with strict: true and zero errors.
    No new @ts-ignore or @ts-expect-error comments introduced.
    All existing tests pass.
    Type safety improved: implicit any count reduced to zero.
    Null safety improved: all nullable values explicitly handled.
  @end
@end
